record.text: Student perceptions of AI coding assistants in learning https://arxiv.org/abs/2507.22900 (https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=46089546)

external.description: The arrival of AI coding assistants in educational settings presents a paradigm shift, introducing a "new kid in the classroom" for both students and instructors. Thus, understanding the perceptions of these key actors about this new dynamic is critical. This exploratory study contributes to this area by investigating how these tools are shaping the experiences of novice programmers in an introductory programming course. Through a two-part exam, we investigated student perceptions by first providing access to AI support for a programming task and then requiring an extension of the solution without it. We collected Likert-scale and open-ended responses from 20 students to understand their perceptions on the challenges they faced. Our findings reveal that students perceived AI tools as helpful for grasping code concepts and boosting their confidence during the initial development phase. However, a noticeable difficulty emerged when students were asked to work unaided, pointing to potential overreliance and gaps in foundational knowledge transfer. These insights highlight a critical need for new pedagogical approaches that integrate AI effectively while effectively enhancing core programming skills, rather than impersonating them.

external.description: **Abstract:** Predicting the aggregation pathways of amyloid β (Aβ) peptides is crucial for understanding and combating Alzheimer’s disease. Existing molecular dynamics (MD) simulations face significant limitations in computational efficiency and accuracy, hindering their ability to model the complex multi-scale processes involved in Aβ aggregation. This paper introduces a novel approach, Hyperdimensional Molecular Dynamics Simulation (HD-MDS), which leverages hyperdimensional computing (HDC) and accelerated sampling techniques to exponentially improve the prediction accuracy and throughput of Aβ aggregation pathway mapping.

external.description: The Two "Black Holes" Explained  To address your question directly: No, this isn't the same £22 billion black hole that Chancellor Rachel Reeves (and Labour) claimed the Conservatives left behind in July 2024, which they said they "discovered" after a Treasury audit. That original claim has been disputed as overstated or manufactured (e.g., by the Institute for Fiscal Studies and Tory critics), but it was framed as an inherited deficit from the previous government.  The "black hole" in the Sunday Telegraph investigation (and the X post you linked) refers to a separate, new fiscal gap that emerged in the run-up to the November 2025 Autumn Budget. This one was hyped as potentially £20–30 billion (depending on media reports and briefings), blamed on factors like OBR productivity downgrades, Brexit legacies, U.S. tariffs under Trump, and broader economic headwinds. However, OBR letters reveal it was far smaller (£2.5 billion in September 2025) and had vanished entirely by October 31, 2025, turning into a £4.2 billion surplus—yet Reeves and Starmer proceeded to brief the public and markets about "hard choices" and a major shortfall to justify £26 billion in tax hikes (e.g., on income, pensions, and ISAs).  In short: The 2024 hole was "inherited and discovered." The 2025 one was a fabricated or exaggerated new shortfall that "existed" in pre-budget warnings but "didn't" once the OBR's full data came out—prompting accusations of deliberate misleading to enable the tax rises and welfare spending (like scrapping the two-child benefit cap).  Key Timeline and Differences Here's a breakdown to clarify the distinction:  | Aspect | 2024 "Inherited" Black Hole | 2025 Pre-Budget "Black Hole" | |--------|-----------------------------|------------------------------| | Claimed Size | £22 billion | £20–30 billion (per briefings and media leaks; Reeves warned of "tough decisions" amid a £30bn gap) | | Timing | Announced July 2024, post-election; tied to Tory "overspending" and audit findings | Emerged in September–November 2025; hyped in speeches (e.g., November 4) and leaks before Autumn Budget | | Blamed On | Tory "economic wreckage," hidden liabilities (e.g., asylum costs, pension schemes) | OBR productivity downgrade, Brexit, Trump tariffs, "worse than expected" outlook | | OBR Assessment | Disputed as not a true "hole" but a policy choice; no major new revelations in 2025 | Sept 17: £2.5bn gap. Oct 31: £0 gap, actually £4.2bn surplus. Confirmed in OBR letter to Treasury Committee (Nov 28, 2025) | | Outcome/Justification | Led to initial spending restraint pledges; later broken with tax rises | Enabled £26bn tax package + £15bn welfare uplift; Reeves claimed it met fiscal rules, but critics say it was unnecessary | | Current Status (Nov 30, 2025) | Still cited in Budget speech as "inherited," but headroom now doubled to £22bn buffer per OBR | Exposed as overstated; No. 10 denies misleading, but polls show 68% want Reeves to resign; Starmer approved the narrative | | Criticism | Tories called it a "lie" to hike taxes; IFS said it wasn't a surprise deficit | Tories/IFS: "Invented" to justify hikes; Badenoch demands sacking for "bribing MPs with welfare" |  Why the Confusion? Media Overlap: Both stories use "black hole" rhetoric, and the 2025 warnings built on the 2024 narrative (e.g., Reeves referenced the inherited £22bn in her Budget speech). But the Telegraph piece focuses on the fresh 2025 scare story, with a senior Labour source calling it "pretty bad." Political Spin: Labour maintains both were real challenges requiring "fair" taxes; opponents (e.g., Badenoch, Stride) argue they're sequential deceptions to fund spending without blame. Evidence from OBR: The November 28 letter is damning for the 2025 claim—it shows Treasury officials (and thus Starmer/Reeves) knew the true picture weeks before the Budget, yet amplified worst-case scenarios from think tanks like NIESR.  This has fueled a resignation crisis: A Mail on Sunday poll (Nov 29) found 68% of voters want Reeves out, with internal Labour grumbling. If you're digging deeper, the full OBR docs (including the letter) are public and confirm the surplus. It's a tale of two holes—one "discovered," one "dissolved"—but both accused of being political props.
